          "body": "13:4-14 establishes the template Paul will follow in all three journeys: arrive at a city, enter the synagogue (13:5, 14), proclaim Jesus as Messiah from the Hebrew Scriptures, gather Jewish believers and God-fearing Gentiles, face Jewish opposition, turn to the broader Gentile population, and move on. Cyprus is Barnabas's familiar ground; Pisidian Antioch is the first sustained Pauline preaching. Between them, two narrative beats matter: John Mark's defection at Perga (13:13) — which will fracture Paul and Barnabas's partnership at Acts 15:36-39, only to be healed in Paul's final letter (2 Timothy 4:11) — and the Sergius Paulus episode (13:6-12), where a Roman proconsul becomes the first named Gentile convert of the mission."
